  { question: "How is overtime pay calculated?", answer: "Overtime pay equals your hourly rate multiplied by the overtime multiplier (usually 1.5x for time-and-a-half) multiplied by the number of overtime hours. For example, at $20/hour with 10 overtime hours at 1.5x, overtime pay is $20 x 1.5 x 10 = $300." },
  { question: "What is the standard overtime multiplier?", answer: "The most common overtime multiplier in the United States is 1.5x (time-and-a-half) for hours worked beyond 40 in a workweek under the Fair Labor Standards Act. Some employers offer 2x (double time) for holidays, weekends, or hours beyond a higher threshold." },
  { question: "What is the effective hourly rate?", answer: "The effective hourly rate is your total pay divided by your total hours worked. When you work overtime at a higher multiplier, your effective rate rises above your base rate. For example, 40 regular hours plus 10 overtime hours at 1.5x with a $20 base rate yields an effective rate of $22/hour." },
  { question: "Do salaried employees get overtime?", answer: "It depends on your classification. Non-exempt salaried employees are entitled to overtime pay under the FLSA. Exempt employees (typically earning above a salary threshold and performing executive, administrative, or professional duties) generally do not receive overtime pay. Check with your employer or the Department of Labor for your specific situation." },
  { question: "How do I calculate weekly pay with overtime?", answer: "Add your regular pay (hourly rate times regular hours) to your overtime pay (hourly rate times OT multiplier times OT hours). For a $25/hour worker doing 40 regular hours and 8 overtime hours at 1.5x: ($25 x 40) + ($25 x 1.5 x 8) = $1,000 + $300 = $1,300 per week." }
